I take a few steps to clean and manipulate the data into a form suitable for modeling. (1) Create a “hit_flag” any time a batted ball in play results in a hit or fielding error to serve as my binary response variable. (2) Create interaction terms for “Bearing” based on pitcher and batter handedness. This is because the ball’s landing position angle with home plate should depend heavily on lefty/righty matchups, especially on the hitter side. (3) Keep only a subset of all fields provided in Trackman data. These will serve as my “candidate regressors” whose predictive relevance I will test when in the feature selection stage. As a note, because spin rate is missing for 1,676 observations, I choose to omit it from consideration.

trackman18_rel_vars <- trackman18 %>%
  mutate(hit_flag = ifelse(h1b == 1 | h2b == 1 | h3b == 1 | hr == 1 | fieldingError == 1, 1, 0),
         count = paste0(Balls,"-",Strikes),
         PitcherRHP = ifelse(PitcherThrowing == "R",1,0),
         RHP.Bearing = PitcherRHP*Bearing,
         BatterRHH = ifelse(BatterHitting == "R",1,0),
         RHH.Bearing = BatterRHH*Bearing) %>%
  select(-c(SpinRate,BatterId,PitcherId,CatcherId,BallparkId,GameId,GameEventId,Season,GameTime,AtBatId,TrackManUid,BatterPositionId,HomeTeamId,AwayTeamId,
            calledStrike,swing,swingStrike,foul,inPlay,h1b,h2b,h3b,hr,hbp,fieldingError,inPlayOut,Balls,Strikes)) %>%
  select(hit_flag, everything())

Next, my feature selection methodology entails performing 10-fold cross-validation on a logistic lasso regression model. (1) I create a matrix of my candidate regressors, which turns all categorical variables into dummies. (2) I break my dataset into a 50% training sample over which to perform the cross-validation for feature selection and choose a minimum lambda. (3) Running cross-validation on this training sample, the lambda that minimizes MSE is shown in Figure 1 below to be roughly 6E-4. (4) I then use this min lambda value to determine which coefficients should be selected from the model over the training sample. The following variables look to be statistically significant: Exit Velocity, Launch Angle, and the interaction of Batter Handedness and Bearing. Due to the significance of the interaction, I will also include the main effects.

x <- model.matrix(hit_flag~.,trackman18_rel_vars)[,-1]
y <- trackman18_rel_vars$hit_flag
set.seed(2000)
train <- sample(1:nrow(x),0.5*nrow(x))

cv_feature <- cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], family = "binomial", alpha = 1)
plot(cv_feature, main = "Figure 1", cex.main = 0.8)

bestlambda <- cv_feature$lambda.min
bestlambda
## [1] 0.0003414691
grid <- 10^seq(10, -2, length = 100)
lasso <- glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha = 1, lambda = grid, family = "binomial")
predict(lasso, type = "coefficients", s=bestlambda)

To evaluate my baseline logistic regression model using the variables selected above, I now perform 10-fold cross validation over the entire sample. We can see that the Accuracy (proportion of correctly identified instances) is about 0.69 and the Kappa (accuracy corrected for randomness) is about 0.21.

xBA.glm <- glm(hit_flag ~ ExitSpeed + Angle + Bearing + BatterRHH + RHH.Bearing, family = binomial, data = trackman18_rel_vars)

It stands to reason that the relationship between these predictors and the probability of a hit would be nonlinear. After all, only launch angles within a certain “barrel zone” are likely to result in hits, while the probability falls anywhere above and below this region. The same can be said of Bearing, due to positioning of the fielders and the spots on the field in which batted balls would result in a hit. Therefore, my preferred modeling technique is a generalized additive model (GAM) which applies smoothing to the specified regressors in order to account for these nonlinear relationships.

Again, I use the selected features above and build my GAM over the 50% training sample. Variables that I intuit to be nonlinear are placed inside spline-based smoothing functions. I account for the interaction effect found to be significant by specifying a smoothing function for Bearing, split out by both LHHs and RHHs. The plots below depict the smoothing curves applied by my GAM.

trackman18_sample  <- trackman18_rel_vars[train,]
xBA.gam <- gam(hit_flag ~ BatterRHH + s(ExitSpeed) + s(Angle) + s(Bearing, by = BatterRHH), family = binomial, data = trackman18_sample)
plot.gam(xBA.gam,se=TRUE,col="blue")

Finally, I perform 10-fold cross validation on my GAM to evaluate performance over the entirety of the sample.

train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
model <-train(as.factor(hit_flag) ~ BatterRHH + ExitSpeed + Angle + Bearing,
              data = trackman18_rel_vars,
              trControl = train_control,
              method = "gam",
              family = binomial())
summary(model)

Here, the Accuracy (0.76) and Kappa (0.46) are both significantly higher than was the case for the GLM. This means that, as expected, accounting for nonlinear relationships in the GAM improved the model’s predictive power.

Finally, I run the preferred GAM over the entirety of the Trackman data. To give an example of why building this hit probability model can prove useful, I map the GAM predictions to their original observations. I then present the following visualizations to underscore the findings of my model:

  1. I map the exit velocities and launch angles that corresponded to xBA > 0.500 to show that my model aligns well with Statcast’s definitions of “Hard Hit” (95+ mph) and “Sweet Spot” (8-32°) batted balls that are likeliest to result in hits.
  2. Using the definition of “Barrels” from (1), I then present an xBA heat map of the strike zone by the 4 most common pitch types and whether or not a player barrelled a batted ball. As we can see below, pitches in comparable areas of the zone are far likelier to be hits if they are barrelled balls, regardless of pitch.
xBA.gam.full <- gam(hit_flag ~ BatterRHH + s(ExitSpeed) + s(Angle) + s(Bearing, by = BatterRHH), family = binomial, data = trackman18_rel_vars)


predictions <- as.data.frame(predict(xBA.gam.full, trackman18_rel_vars, type = "response"))
trackman18_pred <- cbind(trackman18_rel_vars,predictions) %>%
  filter(PitchType %in% c("FB","SL","CB","CH")) %>%
  rename(predictions = `predict(xBA.gam.full, trackman18_rel_vars, type = \"response\")`) %>%
  mutate(barrel_flag = ifelse(ExitSpeed >= 95 & Angle <= 32 & Angle >=8, "Barrel", "Non-Barrel"))


ggplot(filter(sample_n(trackman18_pred,10000),predictions>0.5),aes(x=ExitSpeed,y=Angle,color=predictions)) + geom_point() + labs(color = "Hit Probability") + scale_color_gradient(low = "#56B1F7", high = "#132B43") + scale_x_continuous("Exit Velocity",limits = c(25,125)) +
  scale_y_continuous("Launch Angle",limits = c(-10,40)) +       geom_segment(aes(x=95,y=8,xend=125,yend=8),color="black",linetype="dashed") +
  geom_segment(aes(x=95,y=8,xend=95,yend=32),color="black",linetype="dashed") +
  geom_segment(aes(x=95,y=32,xend=125,yend=32),color="black",linetype="dashed") +
  geom_segment(aes(x=125,y=8,xend=125,yend=32),color="black",linetype="dashed") +
  annotate("text",111,34,label = "Barrel Zone") +
  ggtitle("Figure 2 - Exit Velocity and Launch Angle of Events with predicted xBA > 0.500")

ggplot(sample_n(trackman18_pred,10000)) + 
  coord_equal() + scale_x_continuous("Horizontal location (ft)", limits = c(-2,2)) + 
  scale_y_continuous("Vertical location (ft)", limits = c(0,5)) +
  geom_point(aes(x = Px, y = Pz, color = predictions), alpha = 0.1) +
  scale_color_gradient("Hit \nProbability", low = "#56B1F7", high = "#132B43") + 
  geom_rect(xmin = -0.96, xmax = 0.96, ymin = 1.5, ymax = 3.5, color = "black", fill = NA, alpha = 0.01)+
  facet_grid(barrel_flag~PitchType) + 
    ggtitle("Figure 3 - Strike Zone Heat Maps by Barrel and Pitch Type")
